/**
 üß© JAVA DATA TYPES ‚Äî INTERVIEW Q&A SHEET
 ===================================================

 [1] What are data types in Java?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Data types tell Java what kind of value a variable can hold.
 ‚û§ They help the compiler allocate the right memory & prevent invalid operations.

 Two main categories:
 1Ô∏è‚É£ Primitive (built-in, fast, stored in stack)
 2Ô∏è‚É£ Non-Primitive / Reference (objects, arrays, classes)

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [2] List the 8 primitive data types in Java.
 ---------------------------------------------------
 1. byte
 2. short
 3. int
 4. long
 5. float
 6. double
 7. char
 8. boolean

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [3] What is the size and range of each primitive type?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 | Type   | Size (bytes) | Range (in 2^power)          | Example       |
 |---------|--------------|-----------------------------|----------------|
 | byte   | 1  | -2^7  ‚Üí (2^7)-1   (-128 to 127)           | byte b = 10;   |
 | short  | 2  | -2^15 ‚Üí (2^15)-1  (-32,768 to 32,767)     | short s = 1000;|
 | int    | 4  | -2^31 ‚Üí (2^31)-1  (-2B to +2B)            | int i = 25;    |
 | long   | 8  | -2^63 ‚Üí (2^63)-1  (very large)            | long l = 99L;  |
 | float  | 4  | ¬±2^(-128) ‚Üí ¬±2^(128)                      | float f = 12.5f;|
 | double | 8  | ¬±2^(-1024) ‚Üí ¬±2^(1024)                    | double d = 9.99;|
 | char   | 2  | 0 ‚Üí (2^16)-1 (0 to 65,535 Unicode chars)  | char c = 'A';  |
 | boolean| 1 bit | true / false                            | boolean x = true; |

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [4] Why is char 2 bytes in Java?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Java uses Unicode (16-bit) to support international characters.
 ‚û§ Unlike C/C++, which use ASCII (8-bit), Java char can represent any language symbol.

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [5] Difference between primitive and reference types.
 ---------------------------------------------------
 | Primitive | Reference |
 |------------|------------|
 | Store actual value directly | Store memory address of object |
 | Fixed size | Variable size (depends on object) |
 | Stored in stack | Stored in heap |
 | Fast & lightweight | Slower but more flexible |
 | Example: int, float | Example: String, Array, Class |

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [6] What is the default value of each data type?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 | Type                | Default Value |
 |----------------------|----------------|
 | byte, short, int, long | 0 |
 | float, double          | 0.0 |
 | char                   | '\u0000' (blank) |
 | boolean                | false |
 | String, Array, Object  | null |

 ‚ö†Ô∏è Local variables inside methods do NOT have default values ‚Äî
     they must be initialized manually.

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [7] Why Java is strongly typed?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Every variable and expression has a defined type.
 ‚û§ Compiler checks types at compile-time, preventing errors.
 ‚û§ Example: You can‚Äôt assign a String to an int variable.

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [8] What happens when you mix data types in an expression?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Java automatically performs type promotion (widening).
 Example:
 int x = 10;
 double y = 2.5;
 double result = x + y;  // x is promoted to double

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [9] What is Type Casting?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Converting one data type into another.
 ‚û§ Two types:
    ‚Ä¢ Implicit (widening): byte ‚Üí short ‚Üí int ‚Üí long ‚Üí float ‚Üí double
    ‚Ä¢ Explicit (narrowing): double ‚Üí float ‚Üí long ‚Üí int ‚Üí short ‚Üí byte

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [10] What are Non-Primitive (Reference) types?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Created by users, not built-in.
 ‚û§ Examples:
    ‚Ä¢ String  ‚Üí "Aman"
    ‚Ä¢ Array   ‚Üí {1,2,3}
    ‚Ä¢ Class   ‚Üí MyClass obj = new MyClass();
    ‚Ä¢ Interface ‚Üí Runnable r = ...;

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [11] Why are Strings reference types and not primitives?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Because String is a class in java.lang package.
 ‚û§ It provides methods (length(), substring(), etc.) unlike primitives.

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [12] Is String immutable? Why?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚úÖ Yes.
 ‚û§ Once created, a String‚Äôs value cannot be changed.
 ‚û§ Modifications create a new String object.
 ‚û§ This ensures security and memory efficiency in String Pool.

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [13] What is the difference between char and String?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 | char | String |
 |------|---------|
 | Single 16-bit character | Sequence of characters |
 | Primitive type | Reference type |
 | Uses single quotes 'A' | Uses double quotes "Aman" |

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [14] Can we assign null to primitive types?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚ùå No, primitives cannot hold null.
 ‚úÖ Reference types can hold null.

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [15] Can we compare two primitives and two reference types?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚Ä¢ For primitives ‚Üí use `==` (compares value)
 ‚Ä¢ For references ‚Üí
   - `==` compares memory address
   - `.equals()` compares content

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [16] How are data types stored in memory?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Primitive ‚Üí Stack memory (direct value)
 ‚û§ Reference ‚Üí Heap memory (object‚Äôs data)
 ‚û§ Reference variable ‚Üí Stack (points to heap address)

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [17] Which data type should we prefer for decimal values?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚Ä¢ float  ‚Üí use when approximate precision is fine
 ‚Ä¢ double ‚Üí use when high precision is required
 ‚Ä¢ BigDecimal ‚Üí for financial calculations (exact precision)

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [18] What is type promotion in arithmetic operations?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ Java promotes smaller types to int when evaluating expressions.
 Example:
 byte a = 10, b = 20;
 byte c = (byte)(a + b); // a+b is promoted to int first

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [19] How can we convert String to number and vice versa?
 ---------------------------------------------------
 ‚û§ String ‚Üí int :  Integer.parseInt("123");
 ‚û§ int ‚Üí String :  String.valueOf(123);

 ---------------------------------------------------
 [20] Trick Questions
 ---------------------------------------------------
 Q1. What‚Äôs the default value of a local int variable?
 ‚Üí None. Must be initialized manually.

 Q2. What‚Äôs output?
 byte b = 127;
 b++;
 System.out.println(b);
 ‚Üí -128  (overflow)

 Q3. float f = 3/2;
 System.out.println(f);
 ‚Üí 1.0  (integer division before assignment)

 Q4. char c = 65;
 System.out.println(c);
 ‚Üí A  (ASCII/Unicode of 65)
*/
